{
  "doc_id": "53437",
  "text": "A cooking temperature of 71 • C for twenty minutes is required to inactivate HEV [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The virus stays viable after heating at 56 • C for one hour and remains infectious up to 60 • C [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Although figatellu is usually roasted, it remains strongly associated with HEV infection; cooking does not appear to have a significant impact on seroprevalence in our study (p-value = 0.87). This could be explained by the fact that figatellu is also (i) either eaten without being roasted or (ii) eaten after the necessary cooking times and temperatures have not been respected; (iii) last, pre-roasting handling of the raw figatellu might be a risk [CITATION_5] . In this regard, washing hands after product handling or wearing gloves during disemboweling must be recommended.",
